<lg id="t.6.1.27.b1" type="proverb" n="27.b1"><p id="t6127.p5" n="1-2" corresp="c6127.B.27.b1.1">
<note lang="eng">= Alster 1997 27.1</note>
The rich man's heart is sick, it is very sick indeed (?) -- the man with a troubled heart is sick, he is very sick indeed (?).</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.27.b2" type="proverb" n="27.b2"><p id="t6127.p6" n="3" corresp="c6127.B.27.b2.3">
<note lang="eng">= Alster 1997 27.2</note>
<q>Why are the interest payments so small?</q></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.27.b3" type="proverb" n="27.b3"><p id="t6127.p7" n="4" corresp="c6127.B.27.b3.4">
<note lang="eng">= Alster 1997 27.3</note>
He who carries a light burden can dance.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.27.b4" type="proverb" n="27.b4"><p id="t6127.p8" n="5" corresp="c6127.B.27.b4.5">
<note lang="eng">= Alster 1997 27.4</note>
The conmen (?) are having their say.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.27.b5" type="proverb" n="27.b5"><p id="t6127.p9" n="6" corresp="c6127.B.27.b5.6">
<note lang="eng">= Alster 1997 27.5</note>
People whose houses have been lost turn to their storehouses.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.27.b6" type="proverb" n="27.b6"><p id="t6127.p10" n="7" corresp="c6127.B.27.b6.7">
<note lang="eng">= Alster 1997 27.6</note>
To eat is good. When it comes up again, it is bad.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.27.b7" type="proverb" n="27.b7"><p id="t6127.p11" n="8" corresp="c6127.B.27.b7.8">
<note lang="eng">= Alster 1997 27.7</note>
A troubled (?) mind makes you sick.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.27.b8" type="proverb" n="27.b8"><p id="t6127.p12" n="9" corresp="c6127.B.27.b8.9">
<note lang="eng">= Alster 1997 27.8</note>
On the battlefield plants are torn out.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.27.b9" type="proverb" n="27.b9"><p id="t6127.p13" n="10" corresp="c6127.B.27.b9.10">
<note lang="eng">= Alster 1997 27.9; cf. <xref doc="t.6.2.3" from="t623.h75">6.2.3: UET 6/2 250</xref></note>
<addSpan to="t6127.v1"/>One city does not greet another, but one man greets another.
<anchor id="t6127.v1"/>
<addSpan to="t6127.v2"/><note lang="eng">1 ms. has instead:</note> One city does not salute another, but one person salutes another.
<anchor id="t6127.v2"/></p>
</lg>
<altGrp><alt targType="addSpan" targets="t6127.v1 t6127.v2"/></altGrp><lg id="t.6.1.27.b10" type="proverb" n="27.b10"><p id="t6127.p14" n="11" corresp="c6127.B.27.b10.11">
<note lang="eng">= Alster 1997 27.10</note>
Although he 
<addSpan to="t6127.v3"/>&X;&X;
<anchor id="t6127.v3"/>
<addSpan to="t6127.v4"/><note lang="eng">1 ms. has instead:</note> fled
<anchor id="t6127.v4"/> for &X;&X; miles, he returned after half a mile.</p>
</lg>
<altGrp><alt targType="addSpan" targets="t6127.v3 t6127.v4"/></altGrp><lg id="t.6.1.27.b11" type="proverb" n="27.b11"><p id="t6127.p15" n="12" corresp="c6127.B.27.b11.12">
<note lang="eng">= Alster 1997 27.11</note>
He who found &X;&X; was the one who revealed it.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.27.b12" type="proverb" n="27.b12"><p id="t6127.p16" n="13" corresp="c6127.B.27.b12.13">
<note lang="eng">= Alster 1997 27.12</note>
<addSpan to="t6127.v5"/>&X;&X; coming out &X;&X; afraid and fled.
<anchor id="t6127.v5"/>
<addSpan to="t6127.v6"/><note lang="eng">1 ms. has instead:</note> &X;&X; and fled.
<anchor id="t6127.v6"/></p>
</lg>
<altGrp><alt targType="addSpan" targets="t6127.v5 t6127.v6"/></altGrp><lg id="t.6.1.27.b13" type="proverb" n="27.b13"><p id="t6127.p17" n="14" corresp="c6127.B.27.b13.14">
<note lang="eng">= Alster 1997 27.13</note>
<gap extent="1 line fragmentary"/>
<gap extent="2 lines missing"/></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.27.b14" type="proverb" n="27.b14"><p id="t6127.p18" n="17" corresp="c6127.B.27.b14.17">
<note lang="eng">= Alster 1997 p. 284 A rev. 1</note>
<gap extent="1 line fragmentary"/></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.27.b15" type="proverb" n="27.b15"><p id="t6127.p19" n="18" corresp="c6127.B.27.b15.18">
<note lang="eng">= Alster 1997 p. 284 A rev. 2</note>
&X;&X; reap &X;&X; for the man.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.27.b16" type="proverb" n="27.b16"><p id="t6127.p20" n="19" corresp="c6127.B.27.b16.19">
<note lang="eng">= Alster 1997 p. 284 A rev. 3</note>
&X;&X; my sin &X;&X;.
<gap extent="unknown no. of lines missing"/></p>
</lg></div1><div1 type="segment" n="C">
<lg id="t.6.1.27.c1" type="proverb" n="27.c1"><p id="t6127.p21" n="1-2" corresp="c6127.C.27.c1.1">
<note lang="eng">= Alster 1997 p. 284 C i' 6'</note>
Because they will eat &X;&X;, they seized &X;&X;.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.27.c2" type="proverb" n="27.c2"><p id="t6127.p22" n="3-4" corresp="c6127.C.27.c2.3">
